 Zita Holbourne, national vice-president of the [[Public and Commercial Services Union]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SalmaYaqoob/status/1218223899344809986|title=Thank you to @PCS_union national vice president, @BARACUK chair and human rights campaigner Zita Holbourne for endorsement of my @UKLabour candidacy for West Midlands Metro Mayor|last=Yaqoob|first=Salma|date=17 January 2020|work=@SalmaYaqoob|via=Twitter|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Kevin Courtney]], General Secretary of [[National Education Union]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SalmaYaqoob/status/1218218216125882369|title=Thank you Kevin Courtney @cyclingkev, joint General Secretary of the National Education Union, for endorsement of my @UKLabour candidacy for West Midlands Metro Mayor|last=Yaqoob|first=Salma|date=17 January 2020|work=@SalmaYaqoob|via=Twitter|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Aaron Bastani]], co-founder of [[Novara Media]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SalmaYaqoob/status/1218211013692137483|title=Thank you to @AaronBastani of @NovaraMedia for endorsement of my @UKLabour candidacy for West Midlands Metro Mayor|last=Yaqoob|first=Salma|date=17 January 2020|work=@SalmaYaqoob|via=Twitter|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Ellie Mae O'Hagan]], writer and commentator<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SalmaYaqoob/status/1218198539618091008|title=Thank you to journalist and author Ellie Mae O'Hagan @MissEllieMae for endorsing my candidacy for West Midlands Metro Mayor|last=Yaqoob|first=Salma|date=17 January 2020|via=Twitter|accessdate=18 January 2020|work=@SalmaYaqoob}}</ref>\n}}\n| {{Endorsements box\n|df=yes| title = List of organisations endorsing Yaqoob\n| list =\n{{div col|colwidth=17em}}\n* [[Communication Workers Union (United Kingdom)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salmayaqoob.co.uk/post/the-communications-workers-union-endorse-salma-yaqoob-for-west-midlands-mayor|title=The Communications Workers Union endorse Salma Yaqoob for West Midlands Mayor|publisher=Salma Yaqoob|date=11 January 2020|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]]<ref name=\"LL-whoisstanding\">{{cite web |last1=Chappell |first1=Elliot |title=Who is running to be Labour's West Midlands mayoral candidate? |url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/who-is-running-to-be-labours-west-midlands-mayoral-candidate/ |accessdate=1 February 2020 |work=LabourList |date=24 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Guttridge |first1=Richard |title=Voting for Labour mayoral candidate to begin next week |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/politics/2020/01/10/voting-for-labour-mayoral-candidate-to-begin-next-week/ |accessdate=1 February 2020 |work=Express & Star |publisher=MNA Media|date=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Unite the Union]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SalmaYaqoob/status/1218293753422721024|title=I am delighted @UniteTheUnion endorsed me to be @UKLabour's candidate in May's election. With more than 1.2 million members Unite and its members will rightly have a massive say in which direction the Labour Party will take in the coming months and years|last=Yaqoob|first=Salma|date=17 January 2020|via=Twitter|accessdate=18 January 2020|work=@SalmaYaqoob}}</ref>\n}}\n|\n|}\n\n=== Liberal Democrats ===\n[[Beverley Nielsen]], the party's candidate in the [[2017 West Midlands mayoral election]], was announced as the party's candidate in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/liberal-democrats-pick-business-leader-17580029|title=Liberal Democrats pick Beverley Nielsen for West Midlands Mayor candidate|last=Walker|first=Jonathan|date=16 January 2020|work=BirminghamLive|accessdate=6 February 2020|publisher=Reach}}</ref>\n\n===Green Party===\n* Kathryn Downs<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Martyn |title=Green Party candidate for mayor launches her election campaign |url=https://www.halesowennews.co.uk/news/18027195.green-party-candidate-mayor-launches-election-campaign/ |work=Halesowen News |date=10 November 2019 |ref=Yes|publisher=Newsquest Media Group}}</ref>\n\n===Independents and minor party candidates===\n*Ashvir Sangha, a [[social entrepreneur]], standing as a [[Independent (politician)|independent candidate]].<ref name=\"BM-Ashvirannouncment\">{{cite news |last=Haynes |first=Jane|publisher=Reach |title=Surprise candidate launches bid to become West Mids Mayor on platform of \"youth and inclusivity\"|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/surprise-candidate-launches-bid-become-17788749 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=BirminghamLive |date=22 February 2020|}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigning==\nLabour party candidates were critical of the promises Andy Street made in his 2017 election, noting how he wished to end homelessness in his term when it has in fact doubled.<ref name=\"Ex'n'Str-Lowetheman\"/><ref name=\"LL-Yaqoobarticle\"/> The [[Birmingham Mail]] noted that in November 2019 only 81 of the targeted 225 people were housed.<ref name=\"BM-2020bigyear\"/> One Labour mayor candidate Salma Yaqoob compared Street's performance on homelessness to [[Andy Burnham]]'s [[Mayor of Greater Manchester]], who has reduced homelessness.<ref name=\"LL-Yaqoobarticle\">{{cite news |last1=Yaqoob |first1=Salma |title=The fightback begins with the West Midlands mayoral election |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/12/the-fight-back-begins-with-the-west-midlands-mayoral-election/ |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=[[LabourList]] |date=24 December 2019}}</ref> Peter Lowe, Labour candidate and former leader of Dudley Metropolitan Borough Council criticised Street's isolation of the Combined Authority, how he wasted public money on consultants and how he relies on [[High Speed 2]] (HS2) to bring investment to the city region.<ref name=\"Ex'n'Str-Lowetheman\"/> This argument on HS2 was echoed by [[Anthony Gueterbock, 18th Baron Berkeley|Tony Berkeley]], a Labour [[Members of the House of Lords|member of the House of Lords]], who stated as he resigned from HS2's review panel who said \"Should we go ahead? It depends on whether you think Andy Street\u2019s mayoral chances are worth \u00a3106 billion\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wright |first1=Oliver |title=Andy Street, the Midlands mayor whose fate is tied to HS2 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/andy-street-the-midlands-mayor-whose-fate-is-tied-to-hs2-8lgvpvxsh |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=10 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2019 it was believed that Conservative candidate Andy Street had amassed a campaign fund of \u00a33 million.<ref name=\"LL-Yaqoobarticle\"/> In an article for [[Conservative Home]], Street details how crime is a rising concern in the city region and, although his role does not coving policing and crime, wished to support and work with the Conservative Police and Crime Commissioner candidate for the area, Jay Singh-Sohal.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Street |first1=Andy |title=Andy Street: The Government is providing the investment we need to make our communities safer |url=https://www.conservativehome.com/thecolumnists/2020/01/andy-street-the-government-is-providing-the-investment-now-we-need-to-make-our-communities-safer.html |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=[[Conservative Home]] |date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Prior to the election campaign in December 2019, Street stated that council tax across the city region may have to increase in 2021.<ref name=\"BM-2020bigyear\"/> Street has set targets of delivering 215,000 homes in the city region by 2030 as well as the West Midlands being [[carbon neutral]] by 2041.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosser |first1=Ema |title=West Midlands mayor Andy Street sets out his 2020 agenda |url=https://www.egi.co.uk/news/west-midlands-mayor-andy-street-sets-out-his-2020-agenda/|work=[[Estates Gazette]] |publisher= [[RELX]] |accessdate=1 February 2020 |language=en |date=31 January 2019}}</ref> On 4 February Street release a prospective metro map for the West Midlands city region transport by 2040 should he get elected. The plan features 8 lines for the [[West Midlands Metro]] tram network and 21 new train stations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Billion pound transport plans for West Midlands include underground lines and 21 new rail stations |url=https://www.itv.com/news/central/2020-02-04/billion-pound-transport-plans-proposed-for-west-midlands-include-underground-lines-and-21-new-rail-stations/ |accessdate=7 February 2020 |work=[[ITV News]] |language=en}}</ref> It has been noted that the branding used on the map puts Street's name in green rather than blue and with no branding associated with the Conservatives.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Elledge |first1=Jonn |title=The mayor of the West Midlands has released a map of his \u00a315bn transport plan and it's so, so beautiful {{!}} CityMetric |url=https://www.citymetric.com/transport/mayor-west-midlands-has-released-map-his-15bn-transport-plan-and-it-s-so-so-beautiful-4925 |website=[[Citymetric]] |accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nUpon his selection as the Labour candidate on 6 February, Liam Byrne made reducing homelessness in the city region a core part of his campaign and making the city carbon neutral by introducing a [[Green New Deal]] for the West Midlands.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pidd |first1=Helen |title=Labour selects Liam Byrne as West Midlands mayoral candidate |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/06/labour-selects-liam-byrne-as-mayoral-candidate-for-west-midlands |accessdate=7 February 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LL-Byrnewins\"/>\n\nAshvir Sangha, a [[social entrepreneur]] and former organiser in the 'Brum Young Leaders' programme, is standing as a [[Independent (politician)|independent candidate]]. He laid out his launch into politics with the slogan \"Our West Midlands\", and set out his six key commitments for the city-region.<ref name=\"BM-Ashvirannouncment\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{West Midlands elections}}\n{{United Kingdom local elections, 2021}}\n\n[[Category:2021 English local elections|West Midlands mayoral election]]\n[[Category:Elections in the West Midlands (county)]]\n[[Category:Mayoral elections in England]]\n[[Category:2020s in the West Midlands (county)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2021 West Midlands mayoral election\n| country = \n| flag_year =\n| flag_image = \n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = yes\n| previous_election = 2017 West Midlands mayoral election\n| previous_year = 2017\n| election_date = 6 May 2021\n| next_election = 2024 West Midlands mayoral election\n| next_year = 2024\n| turnout = \n| map_image = West Midlands UK location map.svg\n| map_size = \n| map_caption = Area covered by the mayor.\n| 1blank = 1st&nbsp;Round&nbsp;vote\n| 2blank = Percentage \n| 3blank = 2nd&nbsp;Round&nbsp;vote\n| 4blank = Percentage\n\n| candidate1 = [[Andy Street]]\n| image1 = [[File:Andy Street Mayor.jpg|150x150px]]\n| party1 = Conservative Party (UK)\n| last_election1  = 41.9%\n| 1data1 = \n| 2data1 = \n| 3data1 = \n| 4data1 =\n\n| candidate2 = [[Liam Byrne]]\n| image2 = [[File:Official portrait of Liam Byrne crop 2.jpg|150x150px]]\n| party2 = Labour Party (UK)\n| last_election2  = 40.8%\n| 1data2 = \n| 2data2 = \n| 3data2 = \n| 4data2 =\n\n| candidate3 = [[Beverley Nielsen]]\n| image3 = \n| party3 = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n| last_election3  = 5.9%\n| 1data3 = \n| 2data3 = \t\t\n| 3data3 = \n| 4data3 =\n\n| title = [[Mayor of the West Midlands|Mayor]]\n| before_election = [[Andy Street]]\n| before_party = Conservative Party (UK)\n| after_election =\n| after_party =\n}}\n\nThe '''2021 West Midlands mayoral election''' will be held on 6 May 2021 to elect the [[mayor of the West Midlands]], on the same day as [[2021 United Kingdom local elections|other local elections across England and Wales]], including councillors in all seven of its boroughs and the [[Police and Crime Commissioner]] for the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] [[City region (United Kingdom)|city region]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.itv.com/news/central/2017-04-24/west-midlands-combined-authority-mayor-what-you-need-to-know/ | title=West Midlands Combined Authority Mayor: What you need to know | publisher=ITV News | date=24 April 2017 | accessdate=3 May 2017}}</ref> This is the second election for the post, which had its first election in 2017 due to the [[Cities and Local Government Devolution Act 2016]]. The mayor will be elected using the [[supplementary vote]] system. The election was originally due to take place in May 2020, but was postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Local elections postponed for a year over coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51876269 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIncumbent [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] mayor Andy Street was re-selected to stand in the mayoralty. The [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] selected the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Birmingham Hodge Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Hodge Hill]], [[Liam Byrne]], and the Liberal Democrats re-selected their previous candidate, [[Beverley Nielsen|Beverly Nielsen]].\n\n==Background and election delay==\nThe [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] is [[Ceremonial counties of England#Ceremonial counties since 1997|the second most populous]] [[City region (United Kingdom)|city-region]] of the [[United Kingdom]] after [[Greater London]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Estimates of the population for the UK, England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland - Office for National Statistics |url=https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/populationestimates/datasets/populationestimatesforukenglandandwalesscotlandandnorthernireland |publisher=[[Office of National Statistics]] |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> The position of [[Mayor of the West Midlands]] was created in 2017 following a [[devolution]] deal between the UK government and the [[West Midlands Combined Authority]] (WMCA). The [[Cities and Local Government Devolution Act 2016]] required a directly-elected metro mayor for combined authorities to receive additional powers from central government.<ref>{{cite web|title=Everything you need to know about metro mayors: an FAQ|url=http://www.centreforcities.org/publication/everything-need-know-metro-mayors/#whyare|date=27 June 2016|website=Centre for Cities}}</ref> Under the terms of the devolution deal, the first mayoral term is set to last until 2020, followed by elections every four years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/west-midlands-mayor-elected-4-11635724|title=West Midlands mayor to be elected on May 4 2017|last=Walker|first=Jonathan|date=19 July 2016|work=Birmingham Mail|access-date=23 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017 West Midlands mayoral election|inaugural election]] in 2017, the Conservative candidate [[Andy Street]] defeated Labour's [[Si\u00f4n Simon]] in the final round with 50.4% of the vote.\n\nStreet lobbied the government to integrate the [[Police and Crime Commissioner]] role within the Metro Mayor position in time for the 2020 election. This would have put the role's powers on policing in line with both the mayors of [[Mayor of London|London]] and [[Mayor of Greater Manchester|Greater Manchester]]. However, this broke down as the Combined Authority struggled with Streets lack of transparency.<ref name=\"BM-2020bigyear\">{{cite news |last1=Dare |first1=Tom |title=2020 to be the biggest year in the brief history of the mayor |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/2020-biggest-year-brief-history-17495198 |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work= [[Birmingham Mail]] |publisher= [[Reach plc]] |date=6 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Guttridge |first1=Richard |title=Tory candidate would work with Mayor Andy Street despite plan to abolish PCC role |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/politics/2020/01/30/police-candidate-keen-to-work-with-mayor-despite-plan-to-abolish-role/ |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=[[Express and Star]] |date=30 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the election, the [[think tank]] [[Centre for Cities]] looked at the results of local elections in West Midlands for [[2018 United Kingdom local elections|2018]] and [[2019 United Kingdom local elections|2019]] to make a prediction of the result and found little movement for Labour and the Conservatives, describing the election as remaining on a \"knife-edge\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jeffrey |first1=Simon |last2=Bell |first2=Owen |title=What do the local elections tell us about the upcoming metro mayor elections? |url=https://www.centreforcities.org/blog/what-do-the-local-elections-in-2019-tell-us-about-the-2020-and-2021-metro-mayor-elections/ |accessdate=13 August 2019 |publisher=[[Centre For Cities]] |date=22 May 2019}}</ref> On 12 December 2019 a general election took place in which the Conservatives secured a 80-seat majority, making it the worst seat performance for the Labour Party since the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 general election]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wainwright |first1=Daniel |title=How Labour's 'red wall' turned blue |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50771014 |accessdate=2 February 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rodger |first1=James |title=General Election: All the results from Birmingham and West Midlands |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/general-election-2019-every-result-17412622 |accessdate=2 February 2020 |work=[[Birmingham Mail]] |date=13 December 2019}}</ref> In further analysis, the Centre for Cities assessed the two parties performance in the West Midlands city region, saw the Conservatives having an advantage going into this election.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jeffrey |first1=Simon |title=2020 vision \u2014 What does Thursday's vote mean for May's Metro Mayor elections |url=https://www.centreforcities.org/blog/2020-vision-what-does-thursdays-vote-mean-for-mays-metro-mayor-elections/ |publisher=[[Centre for Cities]] |accessdate=2 February 2020 |date=17 December 2019}}</ref> [[Paul Waugh]] of the [[Huffington Post]] saw the election as a \"tough mountain for [Liam] Byrne to climb\".<ref name=\"HP-Byrneafterreading\"/> In contrast, writer for the [[New Statesman]] Stephen Bush argued this is a difficult election for the Conservatives saying that the change in Labour's [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|national leadership]] and being several months after [[Brexit]] would change the dynamic of the election.<ref name=\"NS-thisyearsmayors\">{{cite news |last1=Bush |first1=Stephen |title=What should we expect from this year's mayoral elections? |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2020/01/what-should-we-expect-year-s-mayoral-elections |accessdate=1 February 2020 |work=[[New Statesman]] |date=13 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrom December 2019 an [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|international epidemic]] of a new strand of coronavirus, called [[Covid-19]], began in [[Mainland China]] and spread across the world from February 2020. On 1 March [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care|Health Secretary]] [[Matt Hancock]] issued a warning that \"all options\" were being considered for handle the quarantine in the UK if the virus spread further, including delaying the local elections, the first time since the [[2001 United Kingdom local elections|2001 elections]] which were delayed due to the [[2001 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth outbreak|Foot and Mouth outbreak]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Busby |first1=Mattha |title=Local elections could be delayed by coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/01/local-elections-could-be-delayed-by-coronavirus-outbreak |accessdate=3 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=1 March 2020}}</ref> On 12 March Association of Electoral Administrators asked the government to consider postponing the elections should the situation in the UK get worse coming close to May.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Buchan |first1=Lizzy |title=Elections chiefs urge government to consider 'legal basis' for postponing local elections over coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-news-local-elections-postpone-legal-aea-a9394906.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The same day, the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] recommended that the elections be delayed till the autumn time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Duncan |first1=Conrad |title=Electoral Commission recommends May local elections should be cancelled amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-news-electoral-commission-may-local-elections-cancelled-a9398131.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=12 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> A day later it was decided to postpone them until 2021.<ref name=\"BBC-COVID19delay\">{{cite news |title=Local elections postponed for a year over coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51876269 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=May's local and mayoral elections postponed for a year due to coronavirus |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-13/may-s-local-and-mayoral-elections-postponed-for-a-year-due-to-coronavirus |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[ITV News]] |date=13 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral system==\nThe election uses a [[Contingent vote#Supplementary Vote|supplementary vote]] system, in which voters express a first and a second preference of candidates.\n* If a candidate receives over 50% of the first preference vote the candidate wins.\n* If no candidate receives an overall majority, i.e., over 50% of first preference votes, the top two candidates proceed to a second round and all other candidates are eliminated. \n* The first preference votes for the remaining two candidates stand in the final count. \n* Voters' ballots whose first and second preference candidates are eliminated are discarded.\n* Voters whose first preference candidates have been eliminated and whose second preference candidate is in the top two have their second preference votes added to the count. \nThis means that the winning candidate has the support of a majority of voters who expressed a preference among the top two.\n\nAll [[Elections in the United Kingdom#Registration procedure|registered electors]] (British, Commonwealth, Irish and European) living the metropolitan boroughs of [[Birmingham City Council|Birmingham]], [[Coventry City Council|Coventry]], [[Dudley Metropolitan Borough Council|Dudley]], [[Sandwell Metropolitan Borough Council|Sandwell]], [[Solihull Metropolitan Borough Council|Solihull]], [[Walsall Metropolitan Borough Council|Walsall]], and [[Wolverhampton City Council|Wolverhampton]] aged 18 or over are entitled to vote in the mayoral election.\n\n==Candidates and party selections==\nCandidates are required to be aged 18 or over and be a British, Commonwealth or European Union citizen. In addition they should fulfill one of the following: be registered to vote in the WMCA area; own or occupy land in the area for 12 months before their nomination; work in the WMCA for 12 months before their nomination; or have lived in the WMCA during the 12 months before their nomination.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wmcaelects.co.uk/candidates/|title=Candidates |work=West Midlands Combined Authority|accessdate=5 April 2017|publisher=Combined Authority Returning Officer}}</ref> Candidates are also required to present 100 signatures of people on the electoral register, with 10 from each constituent authority, and provide a \u00a35,000 deposit to be returned if the candidate receives more than 5% in the first round.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Conservative Party===\n[[Andy Street]] was re-selected as the Conservative candidate in September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/andy-street-to-stand-for-re-election-as-conservative-candidate-at-next-years-west-midlands-mayoral-elections-14991/|title=Andy Street to stand for re-election as Conservative candidate at next year's West Midlands Mayoral elections|work=Solihull Observer|accessdate=17 September 2019|first=Sarah|last=Mason|date=17 September 2019|publisher=Bullivant Media}}</ref> He was previously the managing director of [[John Lewis & Partners|John Lewis]].<ref name=\"NS-thisyearsmayors\"/>\n\n===Labour Party===\n[[Liam Byrne]], MP for [[Birmingham Hodge Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Hodge Hill]], was selected as Labour's candidate in February 2020.<ref name=\"LL-Byrnewins\" /> Five politicians showed interest in standing. Two of them: [[Neena Gill]] a [[Member of the European Parliament]] and [[Lynda Waltho]], former MP for [[Stourbridge (UK Parliament constituency)|Stourbridge]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/news/regional-affairs/birmingham-mp-liam-byrne-hopes-16223283|title=Birmingham MP Liam Byrne hopes to stand for West Midlands Mayor|last=Walker|first=Jonathan|date=5 May 2019|work=BirminghamLive|accessdate=25 May 2019|publisher=Reach}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/politics/2019/06/25/former-mp-lynda-waltho-pulls-out-of-mayoral-race/|title=Former MP Lynda Waltho pulls out of West Midlands mayoral race|first=Peter|last=Madeley|work=Express & Star|publisher=MNA Media}}</ref> withdrew their candidacy. The candidates for selection were Byrne,<ref name=\"Walker\">{{cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/mp-liam-byrne-wins-backing-16245209|title=MP Liam Byrne wins backing of Shadow Chancellor John McDonnell in bid to become West Midlands Mayor|publisher=Reach|last=Walker|first=Jonathan|date=5 September 2019|work=BirminghamLive|accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref> Pete Lowe, a former leader of [[Dudley Metropolitan Borough Council|Dudley Council]] and vice chair of the West Midlands Combined Authority<ref>{{cite news |last1=Madeley |first1=Peter |title=Dudley councillor Pete Lowe joins West Midlands mayoral race as 'anti-austerity' candidate |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/politics/2019/06/03/dudley-councillor-pete-lowe-joins-mayoral-race-as-anti-austerity-candidate/ |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=Express and Star |date=3 June 2019|publisher=MNA Media}}</ref><ref name=\"Ex'n'Str-Lowetheman\">{{cite news |last1=Madeley |first1=Peter |title=Proud Socialist Pete Lowe: I'm the man to win West Midlands Mayoral contest for Labour |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/politics/2020/01/28/proud-socialist-lowe-says-hes-the-man-to-win-contest-labour-cannot-afford-to-lose/ |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=Express & Star |date=28 January 2020|publisher=MNA Media}}</ref> and [[Salma Yaqoob]], the former leader of the [[Respect Party]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Parveen |first=Nazia |title=Former Respect party leader plans to run for Labour in mayoral election |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/18/respect-leader-labour-west-midlands-mayoral-race-salma-yaqoob |accessdate=18 September 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=18 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"LFF-Yaqoobguestwrites\">{{cite news |last=Yaqoob |first=Salma |title=Salma Yaqoob: Whitehall will not be able to ignore me as Labour Mayor for the West Midlands |url=https://leftfootforward.org/2020/01/salma-yaqoob-whitewall-will-not-be-able-to-ignore-me-as-labours-mayor-for-the-west-midlands/ |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=Left Foot Forward |date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Labour Party delayed their plan to announce their candidate in November 2019 due to the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Jonathan |title=Labour gives the Conservatives a two-month head-start in the contest to become West Midlands Mayor |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/labour-gives-conservatives-two-month-16677714 |accessdate=13 August 2019 |publisher=Reach|work=BirminghamLive|date=31 July 2019}}</ref> The candidates were voted on by Labour Party members in the West Midlands, with the result announced in February 2020.<ref name=\"Ex'n'Str-Lowetheman\"/> This was considered late as Labour selected their candidate for the previous election in August 2016 ahead of the May 2017 election.<ref name=\"LL-whoisstanding\"/> Byrne was announced as the party's candidate on 6 February, with 6,948 valid votes being cast, a significant increase from the 3,817 recorded for the 2017 candidate selection. There was also five rejected ballots from the first round and a total of 698 votes non-transferable for the second round.<ref name=\"LL-Byrnewins\">{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/02/liam-byrne-wins-labours-west-midlands-metro-mayor-selection-race/|title=Liam Byrne wins Labour's West Midlands metro mayor selection race|date=6 February 2020|work=LabourList|accessdate=6 February 2020|first=Sienna|last=Rodgers|date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nByrne was considered more [[centrism (politics)|centrist]] than the other two candidates, who were seen as being on the [[left-wing|left]] of the party.<ref name=\"HP-Byrneafterreading\">{{cite web |last1=Waugh |first1=Paul |title=Why The West Midlands Mayoral Election Matters For Labour - And The Tories |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/west-midlands-mayoral-election_uk_5e3c852ec5b6b70886fcbf75 |work=HuffPost UK |publisher=Huffington Post |accessdate=7 February 2020 |date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Labour announces West Midlands mayoral candidate |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-51401388 |accessdate=7 February 2020 |publisher=BBC News |date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Carlon |first1=John |title=Labour ex-minister Liam Byrne to take on Andy Street in mayoral election |url=https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/labour-ex-minister-liam-byrne-to-take-on-andy-street-in-mayoral-election-17414/ |accessdate=7 February 2020 |work=Solihull Observer |date=6 February 2020|publisher=Bullivant Media}}</ref> In Byrne's selection campaign he promoted ideas including the West Midlands being a \"region of sanctuary\" for refugees and [[Municipal socialism|municipal socialist]] policies for the city region.<ref name=\"LL-whoisstanding\"/> He also promoted his positive relationship and endorsement from [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer|Shadow Chancellor]] [[John McDonnell]].<ref name=\"NS-FeeltheByrne\">{{cite news |title=Liam Byrne's victory is good news for Keir Starmer, but not for the reasons you think |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/labour-leadership-race/2020/02/liam-byrne-s-victory-good-news-keir-starmer-not-reasons-you |accessdate=7 February 2020 |work=New Statesman|first=Stephen|last=Bush|date=6 February 2020}}</ref> Journalists including Sienna Rodgers and [[Stephen Bush]] noted that his success in the selection could be seen as a boost for [[Keir Starmer]]'s campaign for [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|national Labour leadership]].<ref name=\"LL-Byrnewins\"/><ref name=\"NS-FeeltheByrne\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Sabbagh |first=Dan |title=Keir Starmer leads the Labour race after unspectacular campaign |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/23/starmer-top-contender-as-voting-for-labour-leadership-about-to-begin |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Selection results====\n{{Election box supplementary vote begin\n| title = 2021 Labour West Midlands mayoral candidate selection| source=<ref name=\"LL-Byrnewins\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box supplementary vote candidate with party link\n| party = Labour Party (UK)